ltruistic behavior directly benefits the individual genotype as well as the group. The value of the monograph is that it provides a robust model in which group selection, pure and unadulterated, can be seen to work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGroup selection (Evolution)xMathematical models. 0aPredation (Biology)xMathematical models. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Ecology.2bisacsh  aGarr-Saunders, A. M.  aGilpin, M. E.  aLevins, R.  aMacArthur, R. H.  aMaynard Smith, J.  aPlague system.  aRosenzweig, M. L.  aTotentanz system.  aWatt, K. E. F.  aWynne-Edwards, V. C.  aaggression.  adominance: ecological.  afitness.  agene flow.  ainterference.  alimit cycles.  aoptimal population density.  apredator migration.  aself-stabilization.  asensitivity analysis.  asexual reproduction.  aterritoriality.  ayellow fever.  azero isocline/isosurface.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999z978311044249640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691209463zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691209463423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691209463.jpg  a978-3-11-044249-6  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Archive 1927-1999c1927d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK